The tangent line must have the same slope as the function $f(x)$ at
$x = 1/2$. Solving for the slope $m$, we get

\begin{align*}
m = f'(1/2) = -\pi\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) = -\pi.
\end{align*} The tangent
line must also touch the function at $x = 1/2$. We use this to solve for
the y-intercept:

\begin{align*}
y &= mx + b \\
\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) &= -\pi\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) + b \\
0 &= -\frac{\pi}{2} + b \\
b &= \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*} Therefore, the tangent line to $f(x) = \cos(\pi x)$ at
$x = 1/2$ is:

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}y = -\pi x + \frac{\pi}{2}}
\end{align*}
